ps described as marriages. But, as Sharon Marcus shows, these women were not seen as gender outlaws. Their desires were fanned by consumer culture, and their friendships and unions were accepted and even encouraged by family, society, and church. Far from being sexless angels defined only by male desires, Victorian women openly enjoyed looking at and even dominating other women. Their friendships helped realize the ideal of companionate love between men and women celebrated by novels, and their unions influenced politicians and social thinkers to reform marriage law. Through a close examination of literature, memoirs, letters, domestic magazines, and political debates, Marcus reveals how relationships between women were a crucial component of femininity. Deeply researched, powerfully argued, and filled with original readings of familiar and surprising sources, Between Women overturns everything we thought we knew about Victorian women and the history of marriage and family life. It offers a new paradigm for theorizing gender and sexuality--not just in the Victorian period, but in our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAmitié fémininexAngleterre. 0aFemale friendshipxEngland. 0aFemale friendshipzEngland. 0aFemmes dans la littératurexEnglandxVerenigd Koninkrijk van Groot-Brittannië en Noord-Ierland. 0aFemmesxHistoirexAngleterre. 0aGroupes de femmesxAngleterre. 0aLesbiansxHistoryxEngland. 0aLesbianszEnglandxHistory. 0aLesbiennesxHistoirexAngleterre. 0aWomen in literature. 0aWomenxHistoryxEngland. 0aWomenxSocial networksxEngland. 0aWomenxSocial networkszEngland. 0aWomenzEnglandxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / LGBT.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/